{{Feminism sidebar|history}}

'''Fourth-wave feminism''' is a [[feminist movement]] that began around 2012 and is characterized by a focus on the [[empowerment of women]],<ref name="Abrahams-Prospect"/> the use of internet tools,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Grady|first=Constance|date=2018-03-20|title=The waves of feminism, and why people keep fighting over them, explained|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/3/20/16955588/feminism-waves-explained-first-second-third-fourth|access-date=2020-06-27|website=Vox|language=en}}</ref> and [[intersectionality]].<ref name="PSA"/> The fourth wave seeks greater gender equality by focusing on gendered norms and marginalization of women in society.

Intersectionality<ref name="PSA"/> and interlocking systems of power are emphasised, and how these contribute to the [[social stratification]] of [[Marginalization|traditionally marginalized groups]], such as [[women of colour]] and [[trans women]]. Fourth-wave feminists advocate (like earlier feminists) for greater representation of these groups in politics and business, and argue that society would be more equitable if policies and practices incorporated the perspectives of all people.<ref name="PSA" />

Fourth-wave feminism argues for [[equal pay for equal work]] and that the [[equal opportunities]] sought for girls and women should extend also to boys and men to overcome gender norms (for example by expressing emotions and feelings freely, expressing themselves physically as they wish, and to be engaged parents to their children).{{sfn|Chamberlain|2017|pp=1–19}} The utilisation of [[Mass media|print]], [[News media|news]], and [[social media]] platforms to collaborate, mobilize, speak against [[Abuse of power|abusers of power]] in seeking for the empowerment of women and seeking justice against [[sexual assault|assault]] and [[sexual harassment|harassment]] is prominent.<ref name="Phillips 930–943"/>

==History and definition==
{{further|First-wave feminism|Second-wave feminism|Third-wave feminism}}

Some feminists argue that in the 1980s, conservative figures like [[Margaret Thatcher]] and [[Ronald Reagan]] challenged gains feminists had made up to that point.<ref name="codigonuevo-2018">{{Cite web|url=https://www.codigonuevo.com/mileniales/cuarta-ola-feminista-llegado-debes|title=La cuarta ola feminista ha llegado y esto es lo que debes saber|date=2018-03-05|website=Código Nuevo|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425111743/https://www.codigonuevo.com/mileniales/cuarta-ola-feminista-llegado-debes|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At the same time, feminists in North America, [[Latin America]], and [[Europe]] had succeeded in some of their goals, including the creation of state-run institutions that explicitly promoted women's rights, or feminist involvement in government; these institutions, however, also weakened feminist movements by letting the state take over implementation of feminist goals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vega Ugalde|first=Silvia|date=2013|title=Comentarios al Dossier: "Nuevas voces feministas en América Latina: ¿continuidades, rupturas, resistencias?"|url=https://biblat.unam.mx/pt/revista/iconos-revista-de-ciencias-sociales/articulo/comentarios-al-dossier-nuevas-voces-feministas-en-america-latina-continuidades-rupturas-resistencias|journal=Iconos. Revista de Ciencias Sociales|language=en|issue=46|pages=103–109|doi=10.17141/iconos.46.2013.58|issn=1390-1249|access-date=26 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426135304/https://biblat.unam.mx/pt/revista/iconos-revista-de-ciencias-sociales/articulo/comentarios-al-dossier-nuevas-voces-feministas-en-america-latina-continuidades-rupturas-resistencias|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live|doi-access=free}}</ref>

European and Latin American fourth-wave feminism began in the 1990s, as ''[[lipstick feminism]]'' and ''[[consumerist feminism]]'' started to come to an end and as feminist activists were rejecting [[queer theory]] espoused by American academics.<ref name="Urzaiz-2017">{{Cite web|url=https://smoda.elpais.com/moda/actualidad/ana-miguel-filosofia/|title=Ana de Miguel: "Considerar que dar las campanadas medio desnuda es un acto feminista es un error garrafal"|last=Urzaiz|first=Begoña Gómez|date=2017-12-21|website=S Moda EL PAÍS|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425121930/https://smoda.elpais.com/moda/actualidad/ana-miguel-filosofia/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":103">{{Cite thesis|last=Guilló Girard|first=Clara Inés|title=El sentido de ser víctima y la víctima como sentido: tecnologías de enunciación de la violencia de género|date=2018|degree=Doctorate|publisher=UNIVERSIDAD COMPLUTENSE DE MADRID|url=http://isonomia.uji.es/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/ZZ.-Actas-Seminario-Int.-violencia-genero-2018.pdf|language=es|access-date=25 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425181934/http://isonomia.uji.es/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/ZZ.-Actas-Seminario-Int.-violencia-genero-2018.pdf|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":113">{{Cite web|url=http://mujerdecantabria.com/estudio-la-recuperacion-integral-las-mujeres-victimas-violencia-genero-cantabria/|title=Estudio sobre la recuperación integral de las mujeres víctimas de violencia de género en Cantabria|last=webdeveloper|website=Dirección General de Igualdad y Mujer|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425185954/http://mujerdecantabria.com/estudio-la-recuperacion-integral-las-mujeres-victimas-violencia-genero-cantabria/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":20">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kamchatka.es/es/feminismo-estrategico|title=Somos la Cuarta Ola; el feminismo estratégico|website=Kamchatka|language=es|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426092329/https://www.kamchatka.es/es/feminismo-estrategico|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":28">{{Cite web|url=https://elcuadernodigital.com/2018/10/29/entrevista-a-beatriz-gimeno/|title=Entrevista a Beatriz Gimeno|last=Cuaderno|first=El|date=2018-10-29|website=El Cuaderno|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426132426/https://elcuadernodigital.com/2018/10/29/entrevista-a-beatriz-gimeno/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":22">{{Cite web|url=https://lasgafasvioletasrevista.com/2019/03/07/somos-la-cuarta-ola-feminista/|title=¿Qué significa que somos la Cuarta Ola feminista?|date=2019-03-07|website=Las Gafas Violetas|language=es|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426135307/https://lasgafasvioletasrevista.com/2019/03/07/somos-la-cuarta-ola-feminista/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Fourth-wave feminism developed slowly, globally via the media and the Internet.<ref name=":03">{{Cite web|url=https://www.estrelladigital.es/blog/tasia-aranguez-sanchez/cuarta-ola-movimiento-feminista/20181023183446356371.html|title=La cuarta ola del movimiento feminista|last=Digital|first=Estrella|website=Estrella Digital|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425111746/https://www.estrelladigital.es/blog/tasia-aranguez-sanchez/cuarta-ola-movimiento-feminista/20181023183446356371.html|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":22" />&nbsp;The wave emerged from a new generation of women who had largely not been informed about previous waves through their education at high school, institutions and university.&nbsp;Knowledge about feminism was gained informally, and it developed a virtual academy where feminists learned that "the personal is political"; it did not emerge from structured feminist learning.<ref name=":03" /> Fourth-wave feminism, like other waves before it, in this period was not about the existence of a single ideology, entity, or collective.<ref name="elperiodicodearagon">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elperiodicodearagon.com/noticias/aragon/pepa-bueno-estamos-cuarta-ola-imparable-feminismo_1321386.html|title=Pepa Bueno: 'Estamos en una cuarta ola imparable de feminismo'|last=Aragón|first=El Periódico de|website=El Periódico de Aragón|date=5 November 2018|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425121929/https://www.elperiodicodearagon.com/noticias/aragon/pepa-bueno-estamos-cuarta-ola-imparable-feminismo_1321386.html|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was about drawing together in collective groups to work together towards a common goal of ending violence against women in order to free them for the options to take the paths they desire; it was about mutual commitment and support to other women.<ref name=":16">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanzadigital.com/provincia/manzanares/yolanda-besteiro-defiende-un-8-m-que-se-sienta-en-cada-uno-de-los-rincones-del-planeta-tambien-en-los-pueblos/|title=Yolanda Besteiro defiende un 8-M que se sienta "en cada uno de los rincones del planeta", también en los pueblos|date=2019-03-09|website=Lanza Digital|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426084505/https://www.lanzadigital.com/provincia/manzanares/yolanda-besteiro-defiende-un-8-m-que-se-sienta-en-cada-uno-de-los-rincones-del-planeta-tambien-en-los-pueblos/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:International Women's Day 2017 - 03 (33202921961).jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|[[International Women's Day]], London, 2017]]

The movement in Spain traces its roots to the [[murder of Ana Orantes]]; on 17 December 1997<ref name="elperiodicodearagon" /><ref name="Urzaiz-2017" /> she was burned to death by her husband in her house in [[Granada]] for speaking publicly on {{lang|es|[[Canal Sur]]}} about abuse she suffered at his hands.<ref name="Albalat-2018">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/sociedad/20181106/sentencia-navarra-la-manada-7132000|title=Juicio a 'la Manada', segunda parte|last=Albalat|first=Miriam Ruiz Castro / J. G.|date=2018-11-06|website=elperiodico|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425181207/https://www.elperiodico.com/es/sociedad/20181106/sentencia-navarra-la-manada-7132000|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="cuartopoder-2019">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cuartopoder.es/espana/2019/01/09/todo-lo-que-la-ley-contra-la-violencia-de-genero-ha-ensenado-a-la-generacion-8m/|title=Lo que Vox no te cuenta sobre la Ley contra la violencia de género|date=2019-01-09|website=Cuartopoder|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425190005/https://www.cuartopoder.es/espana/2019/01/09/todo-lo-que-la-ley-contra-la-violencia-de-genero-ha-ensenado-a-la-generacion-8m/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Early fourth-wave Spanish feminism used television and newspapers as the primary social network.<ref name="elperiodicodearagon" /><ref name="Urzaiz-2017" />&nbsp;Orantes' death took the topic of gender violence out of the privacy of the home and brought it to national attention,<ref name=":53">{{Cite web|url=http://www.concienciacultural.com/nuria-coronado-periodista-y-activista-de-genero-sin-feminismo-no-hay-democracia/|title=Nuria Coronado, periodista y activista de género: "Sin feminismo, no hay democracia" {{!}} Conciencia Cultural|last=ConcienciaCultural|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425121933/http://www.concienciacultural.com/nuria-coronado-periodista-y-activista-de-genero-sin-feminismo-no-hay-democracia/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":63">{{Cite web|url=http://www.que-leer.com/2019/03/08/libros-sobre-feminismo/|title=FEMINISMO AL PODER|date=2019-03-08|website=Qué Leer|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425121929/http://www.que-leer.com/2019/03/08/libros-sobre-feminismo/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and resulted in [[RTVE]] changing its policies on how the station reported on gender-based and sexist violence. Similar conversations took place at other television networks and media organizations across the country.<ref name="elperiodicodearagon" /> Jokes about women being hit by boyfriends and husbands were no longer acceptable on Spanish TV.<ref name=":53" /><ref name="cuartopoder-2019" /> Journalists from ''{{lang|es|[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]}}'', ''{{lang|es|[[El País]]}}'' and ''{{lang|es|[[Infolibre]]}}'' were among Spain's first participants in the fourth-wave, using their positions in the media to talk about a number of issues, mostly centered around sexist violence and its portrayal in the media.&nbsp;They later went on to talk about Spain's gender parity pay problems and the [[glass ceiling]] for them, and promoted taking activism to virtual spaces.<ref name=":83">{{Cite book|url=https://ddd.uab.cat/record/199398|title=Las narrativas de Twitter sobre violencia machista|last1=Matiushkov Badia|first1=Tatiana|last2=Martínez García|first2=Luisa del Carmen|date=2018|others=Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona|access-date=25 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425174235/https://ddd.uab.cat/record/199398/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

The beginnings of this movement in this period took place in Latin America, Argentina, and Poland.<ref name="Arruzza-2019">{{Cite web|title=Cinzia Arruzza: "Las mujeres son las que están enfrentando el ascenso de la extrema derecha en todo el mundo"|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/eeuu/2018/12/09/cinzia-arruza-las-mujeres-son-las-que-estan-enfrentando-el-ascenso-de-la-extrema-derecha-en-todo-el-mundo/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426101920/https://www.infobae.com/america/eeuu/2018/12/09/cinzia-arruza-las-mujeres-son-las-que-estan-enfrentando-el-ascenso-de-la-extrema-derecha-en-todo-el-mundo/|archive-date=26 April 2019|access-date=2019-04-26|website=Infobae|language=es-ES}}</ref> Some of this global desire to act, particularly in a Polish context, came out of the [[World Conference on Women, 1995]] in [[Beijing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nowaorgiamysli.pl/index.php/2018/02/12/czwarta-fala-feminizmu/|title=Czwarta Fala Feminizmu|date=2018-02-12|website=Nowa Orgia Myśli|language=pl-PL|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322115751/http://nowaorgiamysli.pl/index.php/2018/02/12/czwarta-fala-feminizmu/|archive-date=22 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

Social media had an amplifying effect as the fourth-wave feminist movement began to grow.<ref name="Albalat-2018" /><ref name=":13">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/extra/20181106/cuarta-ola-feminismo-motivos-movimiento-twitter-7130787|title=Las feministas reivindican la Cuarta Ola del movimiento y estos son sus motivos|last=Hidalgo|first=Mamen|date=2018-11-06|website=elperiodico|language=es|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426135306/https://www.elperiodico.com/es/extra/20181106/cuarta-ola-feminismo-motivos-movimiento-twitter-7130787|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> 2018 would be the year that fourth-wave feminism began its peak in Spain, Argentina, and Brazil as a result of a number of different factors, with women mobilized on a large scale to take to the streets.<ref name="cuartopoder-2019" /><ref name=":132">{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.es/familia/mujeres/abci-40-anos-igualdad-constitucion-creimos-seriamos-iguales-pero-no-valia-solo-201812060213_noticia.html|title=40 años de igualdad en la Constitución: "Nos creímos que seríamos iguales, pero no valía solo con eso"|date=2018-12-06|website=abc|language=es|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426063542/https://www.abc.es/familia/mujeres/abci-40-anos-igualdad-constitucion-creimos-seriamos-iguales-pero-no-valia-solo-201812060213_noticia.html|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":13" /> Their mobilization also challenged for the first time, the legitimacy of Spain's judiciary, whereas in previous waves the focus had been more on political leadership and acts of the legislature.<ref name=":132" /> The wave in Spain would also face a major challenge, including the emergence of [[Vox (political party)|Vox]], a far right political party who won seats in [[Andalusia]]. Vox was opposed to {{what?|date=January 2020}} and wanted to see it overturned.<ref name="cuartopoder-2019" />  In Argentina, the peak would be around the [[abortion rights]] issue which saw thousands of women with green scarves take to the streets.<ref name=":13" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/entremujeres/genero/feminismo-aborto-cuarta-ola-feminista-victoria-freire_0_IGVMxGhBD.html|title=La cuarta ola feminista: mujeres al poder, pañuelos verdes y la lucha por el fin del patriarcado|last=Clarín.com|website=www.clarin.com|language=es|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122173439/https://www.clarin.com/entremujeres/genero/feminismo-aborto-cuarta-ola-feminista-victoria-freire_0_IGVMxGhBD.html|archive-date=22 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

In an [[anglosphere]] feminist context, journalist [[Pythia Peay]] argued for the existence of a fourth wave as early as 2005, to focus on [[social justice]] and civil rights,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Peay|first=Pythia|title=Feminism's Fourth Wave|magazine=[[Utne Reader]]|issue=128|year=2005|pages=59–60|url=http://www.utne.com/community/feminisms-fourth-wave.aspx|location=Topeka, Kansas|publisher=Ogden Publications|access-date=7 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160908222300/http://www.utne.com/community/feminisms-fourth-wave.aspx|archive-date=8 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and in 2011, [[Jennifer Baumgardner]] dated the start of the fourth wave to 2008.{{sfn|Baumgardner|2011|p=250}} [[Twitter]], the social network most popular with the 18-to-29 age group, was created in 2006,{{cn|date=August 2021}} making feminism more accessible, and giving rise to "hashtag feminism".{{sfn|Bennett|2014}}

In 2013, unsuccessful Democratic gubernatorial candidate [[Wendy Davis (politician)|Wendy Davis]] staged a 13-hour [[Filibuster in the United States Senate|filibuster]] in Texas, in an attempt to prevent an anti-abortion bill from passing. Other women showed support by rallying around the [[Texas State Capitol]], and those who were not physically present used the [[hashtag]] #StandWithWendy. Similarly, women protested the perceived sexist questions (for example, focusing on appearance or love life) often directed at female celebrities by tweeting the hashtag #askhermore.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Chittal|first=Nisha|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/how-social-media-changing-the-feminist-movement|title=How Social Media is Changing the Feminist Movement|website=MSNBC|date=26 March 2015|access-date=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419094625/http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/how-social-media-changing-the-feminist-movement|archive-date=19 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Contradict-inline|reason="As fourth-wave feminism became popular in the United States, other countries were also dealing with similar issues."  The whole section contradicts the global section by positing only that the movement emerged in the USA.|date=April 2019}}

Other feminist movements and "calls to action" have arisen from the fourth wave. One is the "HeForShe" campaign which originated from [[Emma Watson]]'s viral UN Women speech in 2014 and her subsequent activism.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hopkins|first=Susan|date=April 2018|title=UN celebrity 'It' girls as public relations-ised humanitarianism|journal=International Communication Gazette|volume=80|issue=3|pages=273–292|doi=10.1177/1748048517727223|s2cid=149182313|issn=1748-0485}}</ref> Several other incidents have galvanized the movement, including the [[Delhi gang rape]] (India, 2012), [[Jimmy Savile sexual abuse scandal|Jimmy Savile allegations]] (UK, 2012), [[Bill Cosby sexual assault cases]] (US, 2014), [[2014 Isla Vista killings|Isla Vista killings]] (US, 2014), [[trial of Jian Ghomeshi]] (Canada, 2016), [[Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse allegations|Harvey Weinstein allegations]] (US, 2017) and subsequent [[Me Too movement]] and [[Weinstein effect]], the [[2017 Westminster sexual scandals|Westminster sexual scandals]] (worldwide and UK, 2017), and the [[La Manada sexual abuse case|La Manada gang rape case]] in Spain (2018).<ref name="Cosboy-Ghomeshi-MeToo">For Cosby, Ghomeshi, #MeToo and fourth wave, see Matheson, Kelsey (17 October 2017). [http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/kelsey-matheson/you-said-metoo-now-what-are-we-going-to-do-about-it_a_23246129 "You Said #MeToo. Now What Are We Going To Do About It?"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117065436/http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/kelsey-matheson/you-said-metoo-now-what-are-we-going-to-do-about-it_a_23246129/ |date=17 November 2017 }}, ''The Huffington Post''.</ref><ref>
For Savile and fourth wave, see {{harvnb|Chamberlain|2017|pp=114–15}}{{pb}}
For Isla Vista killings, see {{cite news|url=http://time.com/3319081/whyistayed-hashtag-feminism-activism|title=Behold the Power of #Hashtag Feminism|last=Bennett|first=Jessica|date=10 September 2014|work=Time|access-date=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423085856/http://time.com/3319081/whyistayed-hashtag-feminism-activism/|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}
</ref>

Due to the simultaneous existence of multiple waves of feminism – namely the second, third, and fourth – many scholars are questioning the use of the wave metaphor in feminism. However, it is still the terminology most commonly used and most easily understood by the public. As the fourth wave finds much of its definition in relation to the previous ones, it is important to understand what the [[History of feminism|other waves]] were:<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves">{{Cite journal|last1=Evans|first1=Elizabeth|last2=Chamberlain|first2=Prudence|date=July 2015|title=Critical Waves: Exploring Feminist Identity, Discourse and Praxis in Western Feminism|url=https://research-information.bristol.ac.uk/files/50807653/critical_waves_final_revisions.pdf|journal=Social Movement Studies|volume=14|issue=4|pages=396–409|doi=10.1080/14742837.2014.964199|hdl-access=free|hdl=1983/2b137a20-4d1e-41f6-b427-86046c1a32aa|s2cid=145460318}}</ref>

Internationally, comparisons between waves can be difficult. Anglospheric first-wave feminism is second-wave for Europeans and Latin American feminists. Second-wave American and British feminism is also third-wave for Europeans and Latin Americans.<ref name=":72">{{Cite web|url=https://www.homonosapiens.es/podemos-hablar-de-una-cuarta-ola-en-el-movimiento-feminista-monografico-8m/|title=¿Podemos hablar de una cuarta ola en el movimiento feminista?|last=Oliva Portolés|first=Asunción|date=15 March 2019|website=Homonosapiens|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425120245/https://www.homonosapiens.es/podemos-hablar-de-una-cuarta-ola-en-el-movimiento-feminista-monografico-8m/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lahaine.org/mundo.php/evocando-el-68-desde-el|title=Evocando el '68 desde el feminismo de la segunda ola|last=lahaine.org|website=La Haine Mundo|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425120245/https://www.lahaine.org/mundo.php/evocando-el-68-desde-el|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Spanish feminism went through several waves in the [[Franco era]].

Broadly speaking, there are first-wave feminism taking place from the mid-nineteenth century to 1965, second-wave feminism taking place from 1965 to 1975, and third-wave feminism taking place from 1975 to 2012.<ref name=":422">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mujeresenred.net/spip.php?article447|title=El Movimiento feminista en Salamanca después de la muerte de Franco|last=Díez Balda|first=Mª Antonia|website=mujeres en red|publisher=Universidad de Salamanca|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330085239/http://www.mujeresenred.net/spip.php?article447|archive-date=30 March 2019|url-status=live|access-date=2019-03-29}}</ref><ref name=":622">Nielfa Cristóbal, Gloria. ''Movimientos femeninos'', en ''Enciclopedia Madrid S.XX''</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iisj.net/en/workshops/fourth-wave-feminism-sisterhood-and-social-networking-towards-new-citizenship|title=The fourth wave of feminism: from sisterhood and social networking towards a new citizenship?|date=2018-01-24|website=Instituto Internacional de Sociología Jurídica de Oñati|language=en|access-date=2019-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329102930/http://www.iisj.net/en/workshops/fourth-wave-feminism-sisterhood-and-social-networking-towards-new-citizenship|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  Fourth-wave feminism in Spain began in the mid-1990s.<ref name="elperiodicodearagon" /><ref name="Urzaiz-2017" /> When resolving waves around the work of important Spanish-speaking feminists discussing wave theory like [[Amelia Valcárcel]], the Spanish fourth-wave may at times actually represent an international fifth wave, not a fourth one.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Manzano Zambruno|first=Laura|date=2018|title=Apropiación ideológica y feminismo mediático : una aproximación crítica al caso Weinstein y el #MeToo en las ediciones digitales de S Moda y Mujerhoy|journal=Masters Thesis at Universidad de Sevilla, Departamento de Periodismo II|language=es|hdl=11441/78897}}</ref>

Each feminist wave has a separate identity, although they get harder to distinguish and define clearly as time goes on, due to debate among activists and scholars. In an Anglospheric feminist context, the [[First-wave feminism|first wave]] was characterized by the [[suffragette movement]]s and had the aim of legalizing women voting in public elections.<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /> In the same context, [[Second-wave feminism|second wave]] is more difficult to comprehensively define, but is thought to have roots in the 1960s. Its focus shifted to social and personal rights, such as [[Equal pay for equal work|equal pay]], choice over bodily issues, [[sexual liberation]], and resistance to the gendered [[double standard]] in society.<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /> There is much debate among Anglosphere academics and activists regarding the true definition of the [[Third-wave feminism|third wave]] of feminism. It is most commonly understood as a push by younger generations to create a feminism more centered on inclusivity; privileging the plights of [[queer]] and non-white women in their messaging. American poet [[Natasha Sajé]] has written, "[It] is an amalgamation of many different streams of theorizing—including that of women of colour and younger women disillusioned with what they perceive to make up the body of 'second wave' feminism—in intrinsically different formulations than the theorizing coming from anti-feminists".<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Sajé|first1=Natasha|last2=Saje|first2=Natasha|date=1995|title=Then What Is the Question?|journal=Feminist Studies|volume=21|issue=1|pages=99|doi=10.2307/3178319|issn=0046-3663|jstor=3178319}}</ref><ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" />

==Ideas==
British journalist [[Kira Cochrane]] and British feminist scholar [[Prudence Bussey-Chamberlain]] describe the fourth wave as focusing on justice for women, particularly opposition to [[sexual harassment]] (including street harassment), [[violence against women]], workplace discrimination and harassment, [[body shaming]], sexist imagery in the media, online misogyny, [[campus sexual assault]] and assault on public transport, and [[rape culture]]. They also say it supports [[intersectionality]], social media activism, and [[online petition]]ing.<ref name="4thWave-Guardian20131210">{{cite news|last=Cochrane|first=Kira|author-link=Kira Cochrane|date=10 December 2013|title=The Fourth Wave of Feminism: Meet the Rebel Women|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/dec/10/fourth-wave-feminism-rebel-women|url-status=live|access-date=14 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314123922/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/dec/10/fourth-wave-feminism-rebel-women|archive-date=14 March 2016}}</ref><ref name="Abrahams-Prospect">{{cite news|last1=Abrahams|first1=Jessica|title=Everything you wanted to know about fourth wave feminism—but were afraid to ask|url=https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/everything-wanted-know-fourth-wave-feminism|work=Prospect|date=14 August 2017|access-date=17 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117132924/https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/everything-wanted-know-fourth-wave-feminism|archive-date=17 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bcrw.barnard.edu/wp-content/nfs/reports/NFS8-FemFuture-Online-Revolution-Report-April-15-2013.pdf|title=#FemFuture: Online Revolution|last1=Martin|first1=Courtney E.|last2=Valenti|first2=Vanessa|publisher=Barnard Centre for Research on Women|date=15 April 2013|access-date=8 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526211852/http://bcrw.barnard.edu/wp-content/nfs/reports/NFS8-FemFuture-Online-Revolution-Report-April-15-2013.pdf|archive-date=26 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Its essence, Chamberlain writes, is "incredulity that certain attitudes can still exist".{{sfn|Chamberlain|2017|p=115}} Events and organizations involved in fourth-wave feminism include [[Everyday Sexism Project]], [[Kat Banyard|UK Feminista]], [[Reclaim the Night]], [[One Billion Rising]], and "a Lose the Lads' mags protest".<ref name="4thWave-Guardian20131210" /> 

Books associated with the fourth wave include: 
* ''[[Men Explain Things to Me]]'' (2014) by American writer [[Rebecca Solnit]] (notably, a 2008 essay also called ''Men Explain Things to Me,'' reprinted in the book, gave rise to the term ''[[mansplaining]]'')
* ''[[The Vagenda]]'' (2014) by British writers [[Rhiannon Lucy Cosslett]] and [[Holly Baxter]] (based on their online UJ feminist magazine, ''[[The Vagenda]]'', launched in 2012)
* ''Sex Object: A Memoir'' (2016) by American writer [[Jessica Valenti]]
* ''Everyday Sexism'' (2016) by British writer [[Laura Bates]] (based on Bates' [[Everyday Sexism Project]]){{sfn|Bates|2014}}

Cosslett and Baxter's book aims to debunk stereotypes of femininity promoted by mainstream women's press.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vagendamagazine.com/about|title=Letter from the Editor|publisher=The Vagenda|date=19 January 2012|access-date=3 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527012815/http://vagendamagazine.com/about/|archive-date=27 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Bates, a British feminist writer, created the Everyday Sexism Project on 16 April 2012 as an online forum where women could post their experiences of everyday harassment.<ref name="Aitkenhead24Jan2016">{{cite news|last=Aitkenhead|first=Decca|author-link=Decca Aitkenhead|title=Laura Bates Interview: 'Two Years Ago, I Didn't Know What Feminism Meant'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jan/24/laura-bates-interview-everyday-sexism|newspaper=The Guardian|date=24 January 2014|access-date=14 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207012945/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jan/24/laura-bates-interview-everyday-sexism|archive-date=7 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>

Third-wave feminists began introducing the concept of [[male privilege]] in their writings in the 1990s, and fourth-wave feminists continue to discuss it in academia and on social media.<ref name=":11">{{Cite book|title=Feminism and Men|last=van der Gaag|first=Nikki|date=2014|publisher=Zed Books|isbn=9781780329130|location=London|oclc=886112252}}</ref> American [[Peggy McIntosh]] was one of the first feminists to describe the phenomenon of privilege in 1988, calling it (in regards to white privilege) "an invisible weightless knapsack of special provisions, maps, passports, codebooks, visas, clothes, tools, and blank checks."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED355141.pdf?utm#page=43|title=White Privilege: Unpacking the Invisible Knapsack|last=Mcintosh|first=Peggy|date=July 1989|work=Peace and Freedom Magazine|access-date=March 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402042758/https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED355141.pdf?utm#page=43|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Fourth-wave feminists have taken action to reduce and combat this "knapsack" by raising awareness of privileged and unprivileged groups. [[Straight ally|Alliance]] is greatly encouraged by these feminists, who believe that males and other privileged groups can still take action for social change within their communities.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Systems of privilege: intersections, awareness, and applications|last=Case|first=Kim A.|date=2012|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|oclc=799010636}}</ref>

London author [[Nikki van der Gaag]] discusses the damaging effects of raising young boys with privilege, citing the Consultative Group on Early Child Care and Development, "a tendency to privilege boys [...] does not teach teach boys responsibility, nor clarify what will be expected from them".<ref name=":11" /> Fourth-wave feminists have begun promoting solutions to avoid these issues, such as raising children as [[gender neutral]]. Professor of Neuroscience at Chicago Medical School [[Lise Eliot]], points out that infants and growing children are so impressionable that any small differences in raising the child can lead to large personality differences over time, resulting in reinforced gender stereotypes.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Pink brain, blue brain: how small differences grow into troublesome gaps—and what we can do about it|last=Eliot|first=Lise|date=2010|publisher=Mariner Books|isbn=9780547391557|location=Boston|oclc=837684360}}</ref>

Fourth-wave feminists have argued that reinforced [[Gender role|gender stereotypes]] create pressure for men to be breadwinners, as opposed to women, who feel obligated to take on the role of homemakers. Feminists argue that these pressures to conform socially can cause [[gender discrimination]] in the workplace and more widely in society.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Ganesh|first1=Sarlaksha|last2=Ganesh|first2=Mangadu Paramasivam|date=2014-05-27|title=Effects of masculinity–femininity on quality of work life|journal=Gender in Management|volume=29|issue=4|pages=229–253|doi=10.1108/gm-07-2013-0085|issn=1754-2413}}</ref> According to [[Pew Research]], a majority of women working in male-dominated workplaces believe that sexual harassment is a problem in their industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/03/07/women-in-majority-male-workplaces-report-higher-rates-of-gender-discrimination/|title=Gender discrimination more common for women in mostly male workplaces|website=Pew Research Center|access-date=2019-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402031653/https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/03/07/women-in-majority-male-workplaces-report-higher-rates-of-gender-discrimination/|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Intersectionality ==
British professor of marketing and consumer research [[Pauline Maclaran]]<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/0267257X.2015.1076497 | volume=31 | issue=15–16 | title=Feminism's fourth wave: a research agenda for marketing and consumer research | year=2015 | journal=Journal of Marketing Management | pages=1732–1738 | last1 = Maclaran | first1 = Pauline| s2cid=145666422 }}</ref> argues that although celebrities are at the forefront of fourth-wave feminism, ready access to information has enabled the movement to draw greater attention to economic inequalities faced by women than heretofore possible.<ref name="Maclaran-2015">{{Cite journal|last=Maclaran|first=Pauline|date=2015-10-13|title=Feminism's fourth wave: a research agenda for marketing and consumer research|journal=Journal of Marketing Management|volume=31|issue=15–16|pages=1732–1738|doi=10.1080/0267257X.2015.1076497|issn=0267-257X|s2cid=145666422}}</ref>

Regarded as more inclusive of the [[LGBTQIA+]] community,<ref name="Maclaran-2015" /> fourth-wave feminists such as [[Jacob Bucher]] of [[Baker University]]<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/0735648X.2014.949823 | volume=38 | issue=4 | title=Soliciting strain: examining both sides of street prostitution through General Strain Theory | year=2015 | journal=Journal of Crime and Justice | pages=435–453 | last1 = Bucher | first1 = Jacob | last2 = Manasse | first2 = Michelle | last3 = Milton | first3 = Jeffrey| s2cid=143606247 }}</ref> have protested stereotypes surrounding men's supposed uncontrolled sexual desire and objectification of women. He states that gay men specifically are stigmatized by such stereotypes because they lie outside of the typical standard for masculinity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bucher|first=Jacob|date=2014|title='But He Can't Be Gay': The Relationship between Masculinity and Homophobia in Father–Son Relationships|journal=Journal of Men's Studies|volume=22|issue=3|pages=222–237|doi=10.3149/jms.2203.222|s2cid=145751325}}</ref>

British historian [[Amanda Vickery]] claims that fourth-wave feminism marginalizes women of colour who are fighting for inclusivity, neglecting the specific injustices they face to make way for the mainstream struggle.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vickery|first=Amanda Elizabeth|year=2018|title=After the March, What? Rethinking How We Teach the Feminist Movement|doi=10.1108/SSRP-05-2018-0020|journal=Social Studies Research & Practice|volume=13|issue=3|pages=402–411}}</ref>

Canadian art historian [[Ruth Phillips]] argues that fourth-wave feminism falls within the broader agenda of financial, political, and environmental concerns and is recognized as a key factor in alleviating poverty, improving women's health, and achieving economic growth.<ref name="Phillips 930–943">{{Cite journal|last1=Phillips|first1=Ruth|last2=Cree|first2=Viviene E.|date=21 February 2014|title=What does the 'Fourth Wave' Mean for Teaching Feminism in Twenty-First Century Social Work?|url=https://www.pure.ed.ac.uk/ws/files/15148557/Phillips_Cree_Fourth_Wave_for_Open_Access.pdf|journal=Social Work Education|volume=33|issue=7|pages=930–43|doi=10.1080/02615479.2014.885007|s2cid=144660611|issn=0261-5479|hdl=20.500.11820/a5072043-e5e5-4cf1-af19-2207db4e19f7|hdl-access=free}}</ref>

In Latin American fourth-wave feminism, a similar concept to intersectionality is that of ''transversality''.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|last=Langlois|first=Aude|date=February 10, 2020|others=Department of Gender Studies|title=#NiUnaMenos: countering hegemonies in Argentina|url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/gender/2020/02/10/niunamenos-countering-hegemonies-in-argentina/|url-status=live|access-date=October 4, 2021|website=[[London School of Economics and Political Science]]}}</ref><ref name=":7">{{Cite journal|last=Palmeiro|first=Cecilia|date=2018-10-02|title=The Latin American Green Tide: Desire and Feminist Transversality|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/13569325.2018.1561429|journal=Journal of Latin American Cultural Studies|volume=27|issue=4|pages=561–564|doi=10.1080/13569325.2018.1561429|issn=1356-9325}}</ref> It describes "a form of feminism that addresses a wide range of issues in an effort to represent the heterogeneity of society".<ref name=":1" /> Examples include addressing colonialism or racism, economic topics, and LGBTQ issues.<ref name=":8" /><ref name=":1" />

== Around the world ==
{{see also|Fourth-wave feminism in Spain|Hashtag activism}}
As fourth-wave feminism became popular in the United States, other countries were also dealing with similar issues. Although the reactions of local governments differed, the movement of fourth-wave feminists continued. Some of the hashtags associated with the movement included:

* #AndNow or NowWhat<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://quebec.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/01/14/apres-moiaussi-etmaintenant_a_23333272/|title=Après #MoiAussi, #EtMaintenant|date=2018-01-14|website=HuffPost Québec|language=fr|access-date=2019-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325180313/https://quebec.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/01/14/apres-moiaussi-etmaintenant_a_23333272/|archive-date=25 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in Canada
* #WoYeShi ({{langnf||Mandarin|MeToo}})<ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/09/china-women-break-silence-harassment-metoo-woyeshi|title=China's women break silence on harassment as #MeToo becomes #WoYeShi|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=2018-01-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-25|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109041631/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/09/china-women-break-silence-harassment-metoo-woyeshi|archive-date=9 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> in China
* #BalanceTonPorc ({{langnf||French|DenounceYourPig}} or 'ExposeYourPig')<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-global-me-too-20171018-story.html|title=A global primal scream: #MeToo (#YoTambien #QuellaVoltaChe #גםאנחנו أنا_كمان#)|first1=Noga|last1=Tarnopolsky|first2=Melissa|last2=Etehad|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=October 18, 2017|access-date=2019-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326005204/https://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-global-me-too-20171018-story.html|archive-date=26 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in France
* #NotinMyName<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/gender/metoo-campaign-brings-the-rise-of-fourth-wave-feminism-in-india|title=#MeToo Campaign Brings the Rise of 'Fourth-Wave' Feminism in India|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325180311/https://thewire.in/gender/metoo-campaign-brings-the-rise-of-fourth-wave-feminism-in-india|archive-date=25 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in India
* #QuellaVoltaChe ({{langnf||Italian|The Time That}})<ref name=":6">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/how-metoo-has-spread-wildfire-around-world-749171|title=How #MeToo has spread like wildfire around the world|date=2017-12-15|work=Newsweek|first=Catherine|last=Powell|access-date=2019-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325180310/https://www.newsweek.com/how-metoo-has-spread-wildfire-around-world-749171|archive-date=25 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in Italy
* #BoycottAliZafar, #BoycottTeefainTrouble, #TeefaisTrouble<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cutacut.com/2018/07/21/police-detain-protesters-at-ali-zafars-teefa-in-trouble-screening-in-neuplex-karachi/|title=Police detain protesters at Ali Zafar's Teefa in Trouble screening in Nueplex Karachi|last=Khan|first=Manal Faheem|website=cutacut|access-date=2019-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325180313/https://cutacut.com/2018/07/21/police-detain-protesters-at-ali-zafars-teefa-in-trouble-screening-in-neuplex-karachi/|archive-date=25 March 2019|url-status=live|date=21 July 2018}}</ref> in Pakistan
* #BabaeAko ({{langnf||Filipino|I am a Woman}})<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=http://time.com/5345552/duterte-philippines-sexism-sona-women/|title=How President Duterte Sparked an Uprising of Filipina Women|magazine=Time|access-date=2019-03-25|date=2019-07-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325180311/http://time.com/5345552/duterte-philippines-sexism-sona-women/|archive-date=25 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in the Philippines
* #YoTambien ({{langnf||Spanish|MeToo}})<ref name=":6" /> in Spain
* [[Murder of Uyinene Mrwetyana|#AmINext]]<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Lyster|first=Rosa|date=12 September 2019|title=The Death of Uyinene Mrwetyana and the Rise of South Africa's "Am I Next?" Movement|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-death-of-uyinene-mrwetyana-and-the-rise-of-south-africas-aminext-movement|access-date=28 June 2020|magazine=The New Yorker}}</ref> in South Africa

As the importance of social media in "creating and sustaining feminist community"<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /> is an increasingly popular idea, "diversity and creativity continue to characterize feminist activism" around the world in the 21st century.<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /> Communities around the globe witnessed the reflections of "the current, Internet-based fourth wave" feminism and investigated the difference of it.<ref name="Phillips 930–943" /> Moreover, the increasing social power of fourth-wave feminist movements prioritise these issues for elected governments, encouraging them to engage with the "new and young feminisms" of the modern day.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Dean|first1=Jonathan|last2=Aune|first2=Kristin|date=2015-07-04|title=Feminism Resurgent? Mapping Contemporary Feminist Activisms in Europe|journal=Social Movement Studies|volume=14|issue=4|pages=375–395|doi=10.1080/14742837.2015.1077112|s2cid=143104696|issn=1474-2837}}</ref>

For instance, in [[Canada]], after the #MeToo hashtag started trending in October 2017, hundreds of people began to credit fourth-wave feminists with the movement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/metoo-movement-in-canada|title=#MeToo Movement in Canada|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|access-date=2019-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401174416/https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/metoo-movement-in-canada|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Another hashtag, #AndNow, became popular in Canada due to the support of Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]]. #AndNow supported discussing the solution to sexual harassment or abuse in the workplace to help people fight for equity between all people.<ref name=":2" />

In [[India]], there have been several movements or protests with large numbers of women, which have changed the perspective of many in the nation regarding femininity.<ref name=":5" /> These include the 2003 [[Blank Noise|Blank Noise Project]], the 2009 [[Pink Chaddi Campaign|Pink Chaddi]] (underwear) movement, the 2011 [[SlutWalk]] protest, the 2015 [[Pinjra Tod]] (Break the Cage) movement and the 2017 [[Bekhauf Azadi]] (Freedom without Fear) March. Indian social discourse started to focus on long-term and deep-rooted issues, such as gender inequality, sexual violence, child marriage, sex-selective abortions, and dowry-related violence. Many believe it led to the questioning of women's freedoms, choices, and desires in society.<ref name=":5" /> The influence and power of the campaign made the government expand the legal definition of rape, introduced "harsher punishment for rapists, criminalizing stalking and voyeurism",<ref name=":5" /> showed "a new kind of Indian femininity that was comfortable with her modernity and sexuality"<ref name=":5" /> and demonstrates the rise of fourth-wave feminism in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/stopthisshame-girlsatdhaba-whyloiter-and-more-womens-fight-against-sexual-harassment-didnt-start-with-metoo-105711|title=#StopThisShame, #GirlsAtDhaba, #WhyLoiter and more: women's fight against sexual harassment didn't start with #MeToo|last=Kurian|first=Alka|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2019-04-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421142926/http://theconversation.com/stopthisshame-girlsatdhaba-whyloiter-and-more-womens-fight-against-sexual-harassment-didnt-start-with-metoo-105711|archive-date=21 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Ni una menos|''Ni una menos'']] (meaning "Not one woman less") is a Latin American feminist movement originating in Argentina which aims to end violence against women. The movement has engaged in women's strikes, including the [[International Women's Strike]].<ref name=":8">{{Cite book|last=Hosseini|first=S. A. Hamed|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yGAPEAAAQBAJ|title=The Routledge Handbook of Transformative Global Studies|last2=Goodman|first2=James|last3=Motta|first3=Sara C.|last4=Gills|first4=Barry K.|date=2020-06-09|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-0-429-89339-1|pages=460-469|language=en|chapter=Feminized Resistances in Latin America}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite news|last=Branigan|first=Claire|last2=Palmeiro|first2=Cecilia|date=March 8, 2018|title=Women Strike in Latin America and Beyond|work=[[North American Congress on Latin America]]|url=https://nacla.org/news/2018/03/08/women-strike-latin-america-and-beyond|access-date=October 4, 2021}}</ref> ''Ni una menos'' has been described as fourth wave feminism.<ref name=":7" /><ref name=":0" /><ref name="broadly">{{cite web|last=Young|first=Linda|date=December 11, 2017|title=A Women's Strike Organizer on Feminism for the 99 Percent|url=https://broadly.vice.com/amp/en_us/article/3kpk53/-womens-strike-organizer-cecilia-palmeiro-feminism-for-the-99-percent|url-status=live|access-date=October 4, 2021|publisher=Broadly. [[Vice Media]]}}</ref> According to Cecilia Palmeiro, a founding member of the Ni Una Menos collective, "By connecting perspectives such as [[indigenous feminism]] with black feminism, migrant feminism, queer feminism, and popular feminism, we made alliances and enlightened the intersection of violences as well as featured possible strategies of resistance. That is why our movement has been described as a fourth wave of feminism or [[Feminism of the 99%|feminism of the 99 percent]]."<ref name=":0" /><ref name="broadly" />

[[image:EleNao (Porto Alegre, 2018-09-29) 52.jpg|thumb|Protester in [[Porto Alegre]], [[Brazil]], participating in the [[Ele Não movement]].]]
In [[Brazil]], on September 19, 2018, the [[Ele Não movement]] ({{langnf||Portuguese|not him}}), also known as the protests against [[Jair Bolsonaro]], were [[Demonstration (political)|demonstrations]] led by women which took place in several regions of the country as well as the world. The main goal was to protest against [[Jair Bolsonaro presidential campaign|Bolsonaro's presidential campaign]] and his sexist declarations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2018/09/29/politica/1538226863_062834.html|title=Mulheres lideram multidão contra Bolsonaro em São Paulo, Rio e Recife|date=September 30, 2018|publisher=El País|language=pt-BR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://exame.abril.com.br/brasil/15-imagens-que-resumem-os-atos-a-favor-e-contra-jair-bolsonaro-pelo-brasil/|title=15 imagens que resumem os atos a favor e contra Jair Bolsonaro pelo Brasil|date=September 30, 2018|publisher=Exame|language=pt-BR|access-date=22 September 2019|archive-date=28 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328181410/https://exame.abril.com.br/brasil/15-imagens-que-resumem-os-atos-a-favor-e-contra-jair-bolsonaro-pelo-brasil/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Um protesto histórico, menos na tevê|url=http://piaui.folha.uol.com.br/um-protesto-historico-menos-na-teve/|journal=Revista Piauí|language=pt-BR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=2018-09-30|title=Mulheres quebram o jejum das ruas no Brasil com manifestações contra Bolsonaro|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2018/09/30/politica/1538270819_523141.html|journal=El País|language=pt-BR}}</ref> It was being used even among national and international celebrities. [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] was one of the international celebrities who took part in the movement. She posted in her [[Instagram]], where she has more than 12.1 million followers, a picture in which she appears with her mouth sealed by a tape with the saying "freedom". Above, it reads in Portuguese {{lang|pt|"Ele não vai nos desvalorizar, ele não vai nos calar, ele não vai nos oprimir"}} (He won't devalue us, he won't silence us, he won't oppress us).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sousa|first=Silvana|date=28 September 2018|title=#EleNão: Madonna adere à campanha contra Bolsonaro e pede o fim do fascismo|url=https://www.correiobraziliense.com.br/app/noticia/politica/2018/09/28/interna_politica,708917/madonna-adere-a-campanha-elenao-e-pede-pelo-fim-do-fascismo.shtml|journal=Correio Brasiliense|language=pt}}</ref>

Because Latin American fourth-wave feminism encompasses simultaneously distinct movements, many of which are in tension with one another, some refer to Latin American 'feminisms' in the plural.<ref>{{Citation|last=Rivera Berruz|first=Stephanie|title=Latin American Feminism|date=2018|url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2018/entries/feminism-latin-america/|encyclopedia=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|editor-last=Zalta|editor-first=Edward N.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503202647/https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2018/entries/feminism-latin-america/|edition=Winter 2018|publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University|access-date=2019-05-03|archive-date=3 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the more controversial branches emerged as a reaction to and rejection of queer feminism and of [[postmodern feminism]],<ref name=":20" /><ref name="Igualdad">{{Cite web|last=Igualdad|date=22 October 2018|title=El sujeto político feminista en la 4ª ola|url=https://www.eldiario.es/tribunaabierta/sujeto-politico-feminista-ola_6_827727257.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426101920/https://www.eldiario.es/tribunaabierta/sujeto-politico-feminista-ola_6_827727257.html|archive-date=26 April 2019|access-date=2019-04-26|website=eldiario.es|language=es}}</ref><ref name="Arruzza-2019" /><ref name=":28" /> and consists of [[TERF|trans-exclusionary activists]] who reject prominent feminist academics like [[Judith Butler]] and much of feminist theory and seek to create a new anti-LGBT feminist movement by redefining 'woman' as exclusively [[cisgender]] and non-intersex, seeking to reframe the queer feminist movement not as an inclusive but as a watering-down of feminism and erasure of females.<ref name=":20" /><ref name="Igualdad" /><ref name="Arruzza-2019" /> Whereas [[Queer theory|queer feminism]] was inclusive by expanding binary and [[cisnormative]] concepts of gender, these Latin American feminists argue that Butler was attempting to erase the concept of womanhood and thereby women as political subjects,<ref name=":20" /> and reject [[gender studies]], calling it a conspiracy to hide women in academia.<ref name=":20" /> Defining identity through biology instead of gender, and replacing postmodern concepts of femininity with gender-essentialism, they frame queer feminism as a conspiracy to hide 'male' aggressors (trans women) and oppress females.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Espluga|first=Eudald|date=2018-01-12|title=Un movimiento, muchos feminismos: mapa de ideas para orientarse en las trincheras|url=https://www.playgroundmag.net/lit/Feminismos-un-mapa_26183342.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426101924/https://www.playgroundmag.net/lit/Feminismos-un-mapa_26183342.html|archive-date=26 April 2019|access-date=2019-04-26|website=PlayGround|language=es}}</ref><ref name=":20" /><ref name="Arruzza-2019" /><ref name=":28" />

