==Social media==
While previous waves of feminism have encountered such obstacles as rigid sociopolitical structures and a lack of available communication channels,<ref name="Schuller-2018">{{Cite book|last=Schuller, Kyla|title=The Biopolitics of Feeling: Race, Sex, and Science in the Nineteenth Century|date=2018|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=9780822372356|oclc=1050035724}}</ref> fourth-wave feminists harness [[digital media]] as a far-reaching platform on which to connect, share perspectives, create a broader view of experienced oppression, and critique past feminist waves.<ref name="Baer-2016">{{Cite journal|last=Baer|first=Hester|date=2016-01-02|title=Redoing feminism: digital activism, body politics, and neoliberalism|journal=Feminist Media Studies|language=en|volume=16|issue=1|pages=17–34|doi=10.1080/14680777.2015.1093070|issn=1468-0777|s2cid=146135612}}</ref><ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /><ref name="4thWave-Guardian20131210"/>

[[Kira Cochrane]] has argued that fourth-wave feminism is "defined by technology" and characterized particularly by the use of [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]], [[Instagram]], [[YouTube]], [[Tumblr]], and blogs such as [[Feministing]] to challenge [[misogyny]].<ref name="4thWave-Guardian20131210" /><ref name="Solomon-2009">{{Cite news|last=Solomon|first=Deborah|date=13 November 2009|title=The Blogger and Author on the Life of Women Online|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/15/magazine/15fob-q4-t.html|url-status=live|access-date=16 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716184154/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/15/magazine/15fob-q4-t.html|archive-date=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="Zerbisias-2016">{{Cite web|last=Zerbisias|first=Antonia|date=16 September 2015|title=Feminism's Fourth Wave is the Shitlist|url=https://nowtoronto.com/news/feminisms-fourth-wave-is-the-shitlist|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016172423/https://nowtoronto.com/news/feminisms-fourth-wave-is-the-shitlist/|archive-date=16 October 2015|access-date=21 April 2016|website=NOW Toronto}}</ref>

Social-media activism can manifest as Twitter threads critiquing perceived [[transphobia]] in the media<ref>{{Citation|last=Parry|first=Diana C.|title=Feminisms in Leisure Studies|pages=1–12|year=2018|chapter=Fourth wave feminism|publisher=Routledge|doi=10.4324/9781315108476-1|isbn=9781315108476}}</ref> or in so-called "hashtag feminism" campaigns, notably [[Me Too movement|#MeToo]],<ref name="Cosboy-Ghomeshi-MeToo" /> [[YesAllWomen|#YesAllWomen]], [[Chibok schoolgirls kidnapping##BringBackOurGirls movement and protests|#bringbackourgirls]], #NotYourAsianSidekick and [[Black Twitter##SolidarityIsForWhiteWomen|#SolidarityIsForWhiteWomen]].{{cn|date=August 2021}} Girlgaze, launched by [[Amanda de Cadenet]], is an online multi-sided platform that directly connects businesses, companies and brands with women and non-binary creative talent,<ref>{{Cite web|title=girlgaze.com|url=https://girlgaze.com|url-status=live|website=Girlgaze}}</ref> promoting the need for diversity, inclusion and representation across the creative industry. [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] named a group of activists prominent in the #MeToo movement, dubbed "the silence breakers", as its 2017 [[Time Person of the Year|Person of the Year]].<ref name="Zacharek6Dec2017" /><ref>Redden, Molly, and agencies (6 December 2017). [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/dec/06/metoo-movement-named-time-magazines-person-of-the-year "#MeToo movement named Time magazine's Person of the Year"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207033815/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/dec/06/metoo-movement-named-time-magazines-person-of-the-year|date=7 December 2017}}, ''The Guardian''.</ref><ref>For page three, see Thorpe, Vanessa (27 July 2013). [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/27/new-generation-of-feminists-set-agenda "What now for Britain's new-wave feminists&nbsp;– after page 3 and £10 notes?"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111041558/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/27/new-generation-of-feminists-set-agenda|date=11 November 2017}}, ''The Guardian''.</ref>

Other fourth-wave feminist campaigns include the [[Feminist Coalition]], [[Everyday Sexism Project]], [[No More Page 3]], {{lang|es|[[Ni una menos]]}}, [[Stop Bild Sexism|Stop ''Bild'' Sexism]], [[Free the Nipple (campaign)|Free the Nipple]], [[SlutWalk]], the [[2017 Women's March|2017]] and [[2018 Women's March]]es, [[Time's Up (organization)|Time's Up]], and [[One Billion Rising]]. Artistic endeavors include ''[[Mattress Performance (Carry That Weight)|Mattress Performance]]'' and ''[[10 Hours of Walking in NYC as a Woman]]''.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}

Discourse surrounding the topic of [[Social privilege|privilege]] is common among fourth-wave feminists, who argue that members of traditionally dominant social groups should acknowledge their societal privilege and use it to empower and advocate for members of marginalized groups.<ref name="Maclaran-2015" />

==Criticism==
One criticism of fourth-wave feminism is that it depends on technology. [[Ragna Rök Jóns (person)|Ragna Rök Jóns]] argued that "[t]he key problem that this '4th Wave' will face will be the disproportionate access to and ownership of digital media devices." The fourth wave is left with the "inherent [[classism]] and [[ableism]]" created by giving the greatest voice to those who can afford and use technology,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bluestockingsmag.com/2013/08/19/is-the-4th-wave-of-feminism-digital/|title=Is the '4th Wave' of Feminism Digital?|last=Jóns|first=Ragna Rök|website=Bluestockings Magazine|date=19 August 2013|access-date=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327113106/http://bluestockingsmag.com/2013/08/19/is-the-4th-wave-of-feminism-digital/|archive-date=27 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> while the growth of social media in regions plagued by pervasive social injustice remains slow.<ref name="PSA">{{Cite journal|last=Munro|first=Ealasaid|date=September 2013|title=Feminism: A Fourth Wave?|journal=Political Insight|volume=4|issue=2|pages=22–25|doi=10.1111/2041-9066.12021|s2cid=142990260}} Republished as {{Cite web|last=Munro|first=Ealasaid|date=5 September 2013|title=Feminism: A fourth wave?|url=https://www.psa.ac.uk/insight-plus/feminism-fourth-wave|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202070519/https://www.psa.ac.uk/insight-plus/feminism-fourth-wave|archive-date=2 December 2018|access-date=1 December 2018|website=The Political Studies Association}} / {{Cite web|title=Feminism: A fourth wave? {{!}} The Political Studies Association (PSA)|url=https://www.psa.ac.uk/psa/news/feminism-fourth-wave|access-date=2020-06-27|website=Feminism: A fourth wave? {{!}} The Political Studies Association (PSA)|language=en}}</ref>

Critics argue that efforts by large corporations such as [[Dove (toiletries)|Dove]] to capitalize on the movement through activist advertising<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/avidan/2017/05/11/dove-invented-femvertising-but-its-latest-stunt-didnt-wash-with-consumers/|title=Dove Invented 'Femvertising' But Its Latest Stunt Didn't Wash With Consumers|last=Dan|first=Avi|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-04-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421142925/https://www.forbes.com/sites/avidan/2017/05/11/dove-invented-femvertising-but-its-latest-stunt-didnt-wash-with-consumers/|archive-date=21 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> may be inimical to fourth-wave feminism, which tends to be critical of capitalism as an economic system.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Annis|first=Ashley Hartman|date=Winter 2016|title=Which way is feminism leaning? A critique of Sandberg's 'Feminist Manifesto'|url=https://www.library.wisc.edu/gwslibrarian/wp-content/uploads/sites/28/2016/07/FC_3712_Lean-In-Out.pdf|journal=Feminist Collections: A Quarterly of Women's Studies Resources|volume=37|issue=1–2|pages=3–5|via=GenderWatch|access-date=2 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909212417/https://www.library.wisc.edu/gwslibrarian/wp-content/uploads/sites/28/2016/07/FC_3712_Lean-In-Out.pdf|archive-date=9 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>

The conservative critique of fourth-wave feminism is that when women believe that the world is set against them through social systems such as [[patriarchy]], they will abandon all efforts instead of competing with men as equals. Author Joanna Williams writes in ''[[The American Conservative]]'' that fourth-wave feminism encourages women to "call upon external helpmates, like the state, and ugly identity politics that push good men away". Williams also associates the movement with the "[[regressive left]]", claiming fourth-wave feminists are authoritarian and illiberal by dictating acceptable ideologies and policing the speech of men and women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/fourth-wave-feminismwhy-no-one-escapes/|title=Fourth Wave Feminism: Why No One Escapes|last=Williams|first=Joanna|website=The American Conservative|access-date=2019-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402031653/https://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/fourth-wave-feminismwhy-no-one-escapes/|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

It is also argued{{by whom?|date=July 2020}} that when people participate in Internet activism, they may not feel the need to do anything else to help the effort. This type of activism is addressed in feminist punk band [[Le Tigre]]'s 2001 song "[[Get Off the Internet]]", from before social media came into the picture. Later, in 2015, [[Alex Guardado]] asserted in an article on Twitter activism for NewUniversity.org that after contributing their say, people just "continue on with their day, liking other posts or retweeting". Some may think of themselves as activists while never bothering to attend a rally or extend their message beyond their Twitter fan base.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newuniversity.org/2015/03/opinion/hashtag-activism-the-benefits-and-limitations-of-activism/|title=Hashtag Activism: The Benefits and Limitations of #Activism|last=Guardado|first=Alex|date=3 March 2015|work=New University|publisher=University of California, Irvine|access-date=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503053133/http://www.newuniversity.org/2015/03/opinion/hashtag-activism-the-benefits-and-limitations-of-activism/|archive-date=3 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> While various feminist campaigns have spread via social media, the term [[slacktivism]] was coined to describe the mass media users who may speak out on their online platform but do little else to stimulate social action outside of their online platform.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guillard|first=Julianne|date=2016-07-28|title=Is feminism trending? Pedagogical approaches to countering (Sl)activism|journal=Gender and Education|volume=28|issue=5|pages=609–626|doi=10.1080/09540253.2015.1123227|s2cid=148497865|issn=0954-0253}}</ref> This forms part of a greater dialogue surrounding the roles and requirements of activism in an age where communities operate almost as equally online as they do face-to-face.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Kaun|first1=Anne|last2=Uldam|first2=Julie|date=2017-09-19|title=Digital activism: After the hype|journal=New Media & Society|volume=20|issue=6|pages=2099–2106|doi=10.1177/1461444817731924|s2cid=206729225|issn=1461-4448|url=http://urn.kb.se/resolve?urn=urn:nbn:se:sh:diva-33458}}</ref>

Jennifer Simpkins of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' argued in 2014 that fourth-wave feminism had created a hostile, ''[[Mean Girls]]''–like atmosphere, in which women are more likely to tear each other down. "I've actually never once been belittled and attacked by a man for believing in the cause of feminism ... but women are just about lining up to take a whack at the shoddy piñata of my personal tastes and opinions".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/jennifer-simpkins/feminism-fourth-wave-became-mean-girls_b_4616597.html|title='You Can't Sit with Us!'&nbsp;– How Fourth-Wave Feminism Became 'Mean Girls'|last=Simpkins|first=Jennifer|date=20 January 2014|work=The Huffington Post|access-date=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510080539/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/jennifer-simpkins/feminism-fourth-wave-became-mean-girls_b_4616597.html|archive-date=10 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> British scholar [[Ealasaid Munro]] says that the [[call-out culture]] of fourth-wave feminism risks marginalizing and separating people who could serve better as allies over minor disagreements.<ref name="PSA"/>

Women and their gendered issues are not uniform and many variations in issues are a result of related issues such as race, sexuality, and class, and Munro also provides the critique that mainstream feminism is focused on the struggle of middle-class white women.<ref name="PSA" /> Social campaigns that cast celebrities as the face of the movement, such as the [[Me Too movement]], have been criticized, because celebrities often represent the privileged sectors of society, which in turn negate the efforts to expand upon the [[intersectionality]] of feminism.<ref name="Looft-2017">{{Cite journal|last=Looft|first=Ruxandra|date=2017-11-02|title=#girlgaze: photography, fourth wave feminism, and social media advocacy|journal=Continuum|volume=31|issue=6|pages=892–902|doi=10.1080/10304312.2017.1370539|issn=1030-4312|s2cid=148881977}}</ref>

The wave narrative itself is criticised due to perceptions that it is only inclusive of western feminist movements<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /> and that the fourth wave itself takes place in the global north, often neglecting the struggle of women in other regions.<ref name="Phillips 930–943"/>

Other critiques of fourth-wave feminism include its lack of clear evidence in most cases of social media use. Along with this, some argue that though all issues should be dealt with, smaller issues must not be inflated to a higher level by the feminist movement. One example of this is [[Matt Damon]]'s response to the Harvey Weinstein case, "I do believe that there is a spectrum of behaviour, right? [...] There's a difference between, you know, patting someone on the butt and rape or child molestation, right?" Social media also can be seen as ineffective as it brings down "bogeyman" individuals rather than, "invent[ing] a different language or logic that can excise or alter the structures of oppression" as [[Sarah K. Burgess (person)|Sarah K. Burgess]] describes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Burgess|first=Sarah K.|date=2018|title=Between the Desire for Law and the Law of Desire: #MeToo and the Cost of Telling the Truth Today|journal=Philosophy & Rhetoric|volume=51|issue=4|pages=342–367|doi=10.5325/philrhet.51.4.0342|jstor=10.5325/philrhet.51.4.0342|s2cid=149835737|issn=0031-8213}}</ref>

